Careful count of both lakes, with similar totals over the past month as the colony approaches peak nesting production. This count includes: - Ferril Lake: 2 nests (3 young, 3 adults) plus 29 fledglings + adults perched, swimming, diving - Duck Lake: 120 active nests (90 dependent young, both chicks and branchlings), 400 adults, 100 fledglings

At least 2 immature birds - 79 nests with 2 birds - 16 nests with 1 bird Breeding code activities include: C (courtship display), CN (carry nesting material), NB (nest building), ON (on nest)

Locality: Haster Basin Recreation Area, Garden Grove
Observation Details: A majority were adults, and of the adults I saw well enough, three or four showed well-developed "crests".  Not of the crests were white, interestingly, though one seemed to look sort of "grizzled", as seemed to have some white feathering mixed with dark.  I took photos of one of the black-crested adults, as the crests looked so extensive--I couldn't recall seeing one with such extensive crests.  Possibly the wind exaggerated their appearance, as the wind would blow the crests around, and sometimes when the wind was from behind the bird, the crests were blown forward, and appeared to even be in the bird's eyes.  Apparently that's why a few times the bird seemed to be cocking its head to the side, possibly to be able to see better when the wind was blowing the crests over the eyes.  I don't know if this was anything unusual or not, but I just don't remember seeing one (certainly not one with white crests) that looked this long and thick.

This is not an uncommon number at the height of breeding season (e.g., last year, 750-plus birds at peak). Carefully counted, the breakdown is between two locations: Duck Lake rookery: 415 adults, 180 chicks and fledglings Ferril Lake rookery: 3 adults at 2 nests, plus 22 other DCCOs lingering at the lake, roosting in trees and on rocks and snags off the rookery island. Many are young-of-the-year juveniles that have fledged

Probably a 3CY bird which flew in to fish at 08.10, fortunately given that it was absolutely freezing cold. Present since December 15th 1988 according to locals. Smaller Cormorant than Great Cormorant but colouration similar. Quite chocolate brown on the head, neck and mantle shading into bronzy-brown on the coverts. Underside of neck and upper breast paler brown admixed with whitish feathers producing a somewhat mottled, dirty effect. When at rest on a pontoon, it held its tail at an angle with the rectrices spread giving a distinctly spiky look. Legs and feet dark, blackish-brown. In flight the neck was held slightly kinked with head aloft. Spent the initial ten minutes or so fishing before emerging with a Tench of about 16oz in weight which was swallowed whole, still flapping, with some difficulty. It then swam rapidly to the pontoon, leapt out of the water and perched there, wings held out to dry, before settling down to preen. Whole of the bill and gular skin were bright amber, eye distinctly bright greenish, very similar to that of European Shags. A slightly underwhelming first for the UK but well picked out by the finder. British Birds 86(10): p453. Scanned image from colour photograph © David Cottridge; scanned sketch from my notebook.

Some birds dispersed to other parts of the park, but still an extremely active and crowded colony with nests/birds in all stages: A few adults still gathering and bringing nesting materials to nests, a number sitting on nests, some nests with recently hatched young, a number of nests with large, not-yet fledged young (1-5 birds in each), and numerous fledged young in the lake, in the trees, and roosting along the shore or on snags in the lake -- 200 occupied nests -- 25+ empty nests -- Fledglings: approx. 75 in the water, 150 along shore, 30 roosting in trees -- Nestlings/branchlings: 150 (various stages of growth) -- Adults: 275

I was driving across the Hanover Street bridge when I saw a massive raft of cormorant so I pulled over. I counted to 500 by fives and tens and then once I had a sense of what 500 look like in my field of view, I counted it was three times my field of view of 500. No good candidates for GRCO.  EDIT: After reviewing photo count I estimated 1988. Rounding to 2000 to not suggest that level of precision. In total the raft took up fifteen photo frames at 200mm with about 150 cormorants per frame.
